╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║         POLICY VIOLATION — ACTION REQUIRED FOR AI AGENTS            ║
╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

YOU MUST fix the slow test(s). Do NOT raise the limit. Do NOT skip or
quarantine to hide the problem. A slow test is a design defect.

Limits:
  Per-test  : 1 second   (RALPH_PYTEST_TEST_TIMEOUT_SECONDS)
  Full suite: 30 seconds (RALPH_PYTEST_SUITE_TIMEOUT_SECONDS)

HOW TO FIX
----------
1. Replace real I/O with fakes.
   Filesystem   → MemoryWorkspace or tmp_path fixture
   Subprocesses → MockProcessExecutor or monkeypatch
   Network/HTTP → patch at the boundary; never real sockets

2. Eliminate sleep() and real wall-clock waits.
   Inject a clock abstraction and advance it in the test.
   Never call time.sleep(), asyncio.sleep(), or Event.wait() in tests.

3. Refactor production code for testability.
   If the production path forces real I/O, that is a coupling problem.
   Extract I/O behind an interface; inject a fast fake in the test.
   Do the refactor — do not work around it.

4. Assert on observable behavior, not implementation internals.
   If changing the implementation (without changing behavior) breaks a
   test, the test is wrong. Rewrite it to test the public contract.

DONE when ALL hold:
  [ ] Every test finishes in < 1 s
  [ ] Full suite finishes in < 30 s wall-clock
  [ ] No test calls sleep() or polls real wall-clock time
  [ ] No test crosses a real I/O boundary
  [ ] Every assertion targets observable behavior

Full policy: ralph/verify_timeout.py module docstring
         or: docs/agents/testing-guide.md  §'Test Performance Policy'

